  "text": "## Controller Registration with Kubernetes Controller Manager\n\nIn kubernetes/kubernetes v1.32.0, controllers register themselves with the controller manager through a structured descriptor-based pattern:\n\n### Core Architecture\n\n**ControllerDescriptor** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): The central registration metadata type that contains:\n- `name`: Canonical controller name (e.g., \"deployment\")\n- `initFunc`: A factory function of type `InitFunc` that creates and starts the controller\n- `requiredFeatureGates`: Feature gates that must be enabled\n- `aliases`: Backwards-compatible alternative names\n- `isDisabledByDefault`: Whether the controller is opt-in\n\n**InitFunc** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): The registration function type signature:\n```\ntype InitFunc func(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (controller controller.Interface, enabled bool, err error)\n```\n\n**Interface** (`staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go`): The base controller interface that requires:\n- `Name()`: Returns the controller's canonical name\n\nOptional interfaces:\n- **Debuggable**: Controllers can implement `DebuggingHandler()` to expose debug endpoints at `/debug/controllers/{controllerName}/`\n- **HealthCheckable**: Controllers can implement `HealthChecker()` to provide custom health checks for `/healthz` endpoint\n\n### Registration and Wiring Process\n\n**1. Central Discovery - NewControllerDescriptors()** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): This function creates a map of all ~40 controller descriptors. Each controller registers itself by calling `register(newXControllerDescriptor())`. For example:\n```\nregister(newEndpointsControllerDescriptor())\nregister(newDeploymentControllerDescriptor())\nregister(newStatefulSetControllerDescriptor())\n```\n\n**2. Individual Controller Descriptor Definition** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/core.go` and similar files): Each controller defines descriptor factory functions like:\n```\nfunc newEndpointsControllerDescriptor() *ControllerDescriptor {\n    return &ControllerDescriptor{\n        name:     \"endpoints-controller\",\n        aliases:  []string{\"endpoint\"},\n        initFunc: startEndpointsController,\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**3. Controller Initialization via InitFunc** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/core.go`): The initFunc creates and starts the controller:\n```\nfunc startEndpointsController(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, ...) (controller.Interface, bool, error) {\n    go endpointcontroller.NewEndpointController(\n        ctx,\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Pods(),\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Services(),\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Endpoints(),\n        controllerContext.ClientBuilder.ClientOrDie(\"endpoint-controller\"),\n        ...\n    ).Run(ctx, workers)\n    return nil, true, nil\n}\n```\n\n**4. Manager Orchestration - StartControllers()** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): The controller manager's orchestration function iterates through all descriptors and calls `StartController()` for each one (except those marked `RequiresSpecialHandling()`).\n\n**5. Individual Startup - StartController()** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): This function handles:\n- Checking feature gates required by the controller\n- Verifying the controller is enabled in configuration\n- Applying startup jitter to prevent API server overload\n- Calling the controller's InitFunc (which is the \"registration\" step)\n- Mounting debug handlers if the controller implements `Debuggable`\n- Registering health checks if the controller implements `HealthCheckable`\n\n**6. ControllerContext Dependency Injection** (`cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go`): All controllers receive a `ControllerContext` struct that provides:\n- `ClientBuilder`: Access to Kubernetes API clients\n- `InformerFactory`: Access to cached resource watchers\n- `ComponentConfig`: Controller-specific configuration\n- `RESTMapper`: API resource discovery\n- `ResyncPeriod`: Function that returns random sync periods (prevents thundering herd)\n\n**7. Actual Controller Implementation** (`pkg/controller/endpoint/endpoints_controller.go`): The concrete controller implements:\n- Constructor (`NewEndpointController`) that registers event handlers on informers\n- A `Run()` method that starts worker goroutines processing a work queue\n- Event handlers that enqueue items when resources change\n- Worker methods that process items and reconcile state\n\n### Reconciliation Loop\n\nThe manager's reconcile loop is implemented through:\n1. **Event-driven queueing**: Informers watch for resource changes and trigger event handlers\n2. **Work queue**: Items are added to a rate-limited work queue\n3. **Worker goroutines**: Multiple workers process items from the queue\n4. **Reconciliation**: Each worker item triggers comparison and reconciliation of desired vs actual state\n5. **Retries**: Failed items are re-queued with exponential backoff\n\n### Leader Election Integration\n\nControllers are registered and started within a leader election context. Only the leader node runs the controllers, ensuring single-writer semantics. The `Run()` function in `controllermanager.go` uses `leaderElectAndRun()` to gate controller startup on leader election.\n\n### Key Differences from controller-runtime\n\nWhile the task mentions controller-runtime patterns (Reconciler interface, SetupWithManager), Kubernetes controllers use its own patterns:\n- Instead of `SetupWithManager()`, Kubernetes uses the `InitFunc` approach\n- Instead of a single `Reconcile()` method, Kubernetes controllers implement `Run()` methods with work queues\n- Instead of manager auto-wiring, Kubernetes manually creates and passes clients/informers via `ControllerContext`\n\nThe patterns are semantically equivalent but architecturally different, with Kubernetes' approach being lower-level and more explicit about resource management."
}

